The KYT fee does not happen on ckBTC transactions. It happens on BTC inflows only. And the way the contract works, we pay upfront for many many requests over the year, and then we are reimbursed over the year as people wrap their BTC to ckBTC. We don't get enough transactions though, so this is a significant loss for us. Might sound great to earn fees on KYT, but we don't mark up the fee at all. And we don't get enough usage. And even if we did, we pay that much per call anyway. So no profit potential here for us. Just an annoying thing we had to do to get ckBTC working the way we wanted with Dfinity.

We don't WANT to be the provider here. It is a thankless job, increases our legal liability, with no profit potential. We did it because at the time, KYT was needed to get ckBTC off the ground and we wanted it to happen.

Yeah, we haven't done a good job communicating on this end.  Here's what happens when you reach level 4:
- You will have the ability to inscribe your Sentinel to Bitcoin, meaning it will be a true ordinal that will live forward on the OG blockchain.  It will also be listable on other marketplaces, but that also requires someone setting up the collection on another marketplace.
- Only inscribed Sentinels will be able to play Game 2, which will be a long term, mass multiplayer cooperative game.  The game will make use of the runes you are farming on your missions.  I think most people will find Game 2 to be a killer use case of Sentinels that will attract ordinal collectors and NFT collectors from other ecosystems like SOL to the collection.  More info will come out as Sentinels reach level 4.
- We are also exploring "play your way to decentralization", utilizing Game 2's mechanics for continued decentralization of the collection (voting, etc), but this idea is still in its infancy and needs to be fleshed out more

What do you see the significant downsides to approve/transferFrom being?

The way I understand it, these methods do nothing more than enable permissionless building upon:
-  user **approves** x-platform access to transferFrom call, or even multiple platforms access to.
- the **allowances** method allows anyone to check who is approved to transfer each token. 
- the **transferFrom** method is then used to finalze the contract, permissionlessly.

If the community will be covering the cycles and they're to be blackholed, decentralization that I would be comfortable with years into the future would be all platforms having access to the same primitive methods in order to architect their own solutions and functionality, similar to how it works on ETH. 

Currently the baked-in Toniq commissions and Approve/TransferFrom EXT methods being disabled can be justified by someone having to pay the cycles, and I agree to an extent, though I wish there were a way for the frontend that drives the sale to receive part of the commission through the smart-contract similarly to how platform agnostic variations of the standard are doing it.

referenced_message.content:
The point I am trying to make here is if you believe in Ordinals (NFTs, aka images connected to sats), you have to be ok with trusting the ordinals team. It is a fairly centralized protocol governed by Casey and co. It has come a long way since the beginning, but you are 100% trusting the off-chain ordinals team/protocol/indexer. So you could argue that Ordinals are not non-custodial because you don't truly, exclusively own your own asset forever. You have to trust.

On ETH, it is very easy to fully decentralize a smart contract. You just pay the storage costs, and you're good to go. Pay $1-2k and store your smart contract on ETH. It is stored there forever. No maintenance required. Nobody can change it. 

On ICP, it is very hard to fully decentralize a smart contract. The protocol is constantly changing and upgrading, so things that you previously deployed might actually not work in the future (occasionally breaking changes get pushed out). Then you have to deal with storage, aka increasing state (there's only so much storage in a canister, and if you go too high your canister dies). Then you have to deal with lots of limitations in the protocol (instruction limit, cross-canister call wait times, boundary node DDOS protection, etc). 

Our goal is to fully decentralize everything on the ICP side (Toniq/Entrepot) as well as the BTC side (Bioniq). We are on a path of progressive decentralization. We finally have a path forward on the ICP side (essentially rip marketplace methods out of each canister, trim them down so they are super simple - just registry, transfer, images) and then we can blackhole them all and turn cycles management over to the community. On the Bioniq side, we have a nice multi-sig setup all ready to go, we just need to find the right signers for it. And then eventually we'll push for blackholing these canisters as well once we feel the Internet Computer Protocol is stable enough to handle it.

referenced_message.content:
The point I am trying to make here is if you believe in Ordinals (NFTs, aka images connected to sats), you have to be ok with trusting the ordinals team. It is a fairly centralized protocol governed by Casey and co. It has come a long way since the beginning, but you are 100% trusting the off-chain ordinals team/protocol/indexer. So you could argue that Ordinals are not non-custodial because you don't truly, exclusively own your own asset forever. You have to trust.

On ETH, it is very easy to fully decentralize a smart contract. You just pay the storage costs, and you're good to go. Pay $1-2k and store your smart contract on ETH. It is stored there forever. No maintenance required. Nobody can change it. 

On ICP, it is very hard to fully decentralize a smart contract. The protocol is constantly changing and upgrading, so things that you previously deployed might actually not work in the future (occasionally breaking changes get pushed out). Then you have to deal with storage, aka increasing state (there's only so much storage in a canister, and if you go too high your canister dies).
